      <div resp="part:emfr" type="translation">
        <p n="1">
   Prosperity!
</p>
        <p n="1-3">
   Fifty-second year of the victorious king Nandīśvaravarman.
</p>
        <p n="4-11">
   On the day when Vallavaraiyaṉ marched <supplied reason="explanation">literally: "came"</supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">with</supplied> his army upon <supplied reason="explanation">
            <foreign>mēl</foreign>
          </supplied> Perumāṉaṭikaḷ and destroyed Veṇkuḻikkōṭṭai, while Vāṇaraiyar, his uncle <supplied reason="explanation">
            <foreign>māmaṭi</foreign>
          </supplied> said <supplied reason="explanation">to him</supplied> “Let us proceed <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tirika</foreign>, that is, "Let us march against him, that is, Vallavaraiyaṉ</supplied>”, Kaṅkatiyaraiyar, who owns Kaṟkāṭṭūr, having <supplied reason="subaudible">thus</supplied> poceeded <supplied reason="explanation">
            <foreign>tirintu</foreign>
          </supplied>, fell <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>paṭṭār</foreign>, that is "died"</supplied>.
</p>
        <p n="11-12">
   Planting of the stone <supplied reason="explanation">
            <foreign>kaṉ-ṉāṭu</foreign>
          </supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">by</supplied> Peruṅkaṅkar.
</p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary">
        <p>
      On the identity of the protagonists: Perumāṉaṭikaḷ, Vallavaraiyaṉ, Vāṇaraiyar, Kaṅkatiyaraiyar.
   </p>
        <p n="8">
      <foreign>māmaṭi</foreign>. Alternative translation = father-in-law.
   </p>
        <p n="11">
      On <foreign>kaṉ-ṉāṭu</foreign>, see ...
   </p>
